---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Basement Engineering - Hampstead Architects & Interiors"
  description="Specialist basement excavation, underpinning, and Party Wall Act compliance for single and double-depth basements in London. Expert structural coordination and neighbour liaison."
  schemaType="Service"
>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-charcoal text-cream">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12 text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl font-serif font-light mb-6">
        Basement Engineering
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl font-light text-cream/90 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        London's most complex residential projects happen underground. We've guided 200+ basement excavations without litigation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why Basements Are Different -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="grid-editorial">
      <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-8 lg:col-start-3">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-8">Why Basements Require Specialists</h2>

        <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Excavating beneath an existing Victorian terrace is <strong>structural surgery</strong>. Get it wrong, and your neighbour's wall cracks. Your planning permission gets revoked. Your budget doubles.
          </p>

          <p>
            Unlike above-ground extensions, basements involve:
          </p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
            <li><strong>Party Wall Act compliance</strong> - Legal notices to adjoining owners, mandatory surveyor appointments</li>
            <li><strong>Underpinning existing foundations</strong> - Sequenced excavation to prevent subsidence</li>
            <li><strong>Waterproofing to BS 8102</strong> - Multi-layer tanking systems, sump pumps, drainage</li>
            <li><strong>Structural calculations</strong> - Soil load bearing, lateral thrust, steel beam sizing</li>
            <li><strong>Neighbour relations</strong> - Managing disputes, monitoring adjacent properties, damage protocols</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-xl text-charcoal/90 font-light italic border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper pl-6">
            Most architects design basements. Few have managed the Party Wall Act minefield 200 times. That's where we come in.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Cost Breakdown -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-warm-stone">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-12 text-center">The Real Cost of Basements</h2>
      <p class="text-center text-lg text-charcoal/80 mb-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        Transparency first. Here's what basement excavation actually costs in Hampstead, Belsize Park, and Primrose Hill (2025 pricing).
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <!-- Single-Depth Basement -->
        <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Single-Depth Basement</h3>
          <p class="text-base mb-6 leading-relaxed text-charcoal/80">
            2.4m floor-to-ceiling height. Most common option for terraced houses. Typical uses: home cinema, gym, wine cellar, guest bedroom.
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Excavation & underpinning</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£8,000-12,000/m³</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Waterproofing (Type A tanking)</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£150-250/m²</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Structural steelwork</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£15,000-30,000</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Party Wall surveyors (both sides)</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£3,000-6,000</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Structural engineer fees</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£5,000-8,000</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pt-4 border-t border-charcoal/20">
            <div class="flex justify-between text-lg font-medium">
              <span>Typical 40m³ basement</span>
              <span class="text-oxidized-copper">£320,000-480,000</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-charcoal/60 mt-2">
              Excludes internal finishes, HVAC, lighting. Add £80-150k for fitted-out space.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Double-Depth Basement -->
        <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-serif font-light mb-4 text-oxidized-copper">Double-Depth Basement</h3>
          <p class="text-base mb-6 leading-relaxed text-charcoal/80">
            Two floors below ground (4.8m+ excavation). Requires crane access, sequenced dig, intensive neighbour coordination. High-end only.
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Excavation & underpinning</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£12,000-18,000/m³</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Waterproofing (Type C system)</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£250-400/m²</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Structural steelwork</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£40,000-80,000</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Party Wall surveyors + monitoring</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£8,000-15,000</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-between text-sm">
              <span class="text-charcoal/70">Specialist structural engineer</span>
              <span class="font-medium">£12,000-20,000</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="pt-4 border-t border-charcoal/20">
            <div class="flex justify-between text-lg font-medium">
              <span>Typical 80m³ basement</span>
              <span class="text-oxidized-copper">£960,000-1,440,000</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-charcoal/60 mt-2">
              Excludes finishes, pool installation, cinema fit-out. Projects often exceed £2M total.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 bg-oxidized-copper/10 border border-oxidized-copper/30 p-6">
        <p class="text-base text-charcoal/90 leading-relaxed">
          <strong>Why such variation?</strong> Costs depend on: soil type (clay vs. gravel), proximity to neighbours, access constraints (can a crane fit in your street?), waterproofing complexity, and planning requirements (Camden sometimes demands environmental impact assessments).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Party Wall Act Expertise -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="grid-editorial">
      <div class="col-span-12 lg:col-span-10 lg:col-start-2">
        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-8 md:p-12 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-6 text-oxidized-copper">
            The Party Wall Act Minefield
          </h2>

          <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              The <strong>Party Wall etc. Act 1996</strong> is unavoidable for basement excavations. It governs work affecting shared walls, boundaries, and foundations within 3-6 meters of neighbouring properties.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mt-8 mb-4">How the Process Works</h3>

            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="bg-white p-6 border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper">
                <h4 class="font-medium mb-2">1. Party Wall Notices (2 months before work)</h4>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80">
                  You serve legal notices to all adjoining owners describing the excavation. They have 14 days to consent or dissent. Most dissent (it's the safer legal option).
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-6 border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper">
                <h4 class="font-medium mb-2">2. Surveyor Appointments</h4>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80">
                  If neighbours dissent, both sides appoint Party Wall Surveyors. You pay for both (yes, you pay for their surveyor too). Costs: £3,000-15,000 total depending on complexity.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-6 border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper">
                <h4 class="font-medium mb-2">3. Party Wall Award</h4>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80">
                  Surveyors agree on a schedule of condition (photos/videos of neighbour's property pre-work), method statements, and working hours. This becomes legally binding.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white p-6 border-l-3 border-oxidized-copper">
                <h4 class="font-medium mb-2">4. Ongoing Monitoring</h4>
                <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80">
                  During excavation, surveyors monitor for cracks, movement, or damage. If issues arise, work stops until resolved. Post-completion inspections ensure no long-term damage.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="mt-8 bg-white p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
              <strong>Our Role:</strong> We coordinate the entire Party Wall process—selecting experienced surveyors, managing neighbour communications, and ensuring compliance without antagonizing relationships. Our track record: <strong>200+ basement projects, zero litigation.</strong>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Common Basement Designs -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-charcoal text-cream">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-12 text-center">What Goes in Hampstead Basements</h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4">Utility & Wellness</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-cream/80">
            <li>• Home gym with natural light well</li>
            <li>• Wine cellar (climate-controlled, 500+ bottles)</li>
            <li>• Steam room / sauna</li>
            <li>• Laundry and storage</li>
            <li>• Plant room (HVAC, water softener)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4">Entertainment</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-cream/80">
            <li>• Home cinema (Dolby Atmos soundproofing)</li>
            <li>• Games room (pool table, bar)</li>
            <li>• Music studio / practice room</li>
            <li>• Guest bedroom with en-suite</li>
            <li>• Children's playroom</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone/10 border border-cream/20 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-4">Luxury (Double-Depth)</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-cream/80">
            <li>• Swimming pool (8m lap pool typical)</li>
            <li>• Spa complex (jacuzzi, treatment room)</li>
            <li>• Staff accommodation</li>
            <li>• Car lift (for underground garage)</li>
            <li>• Art vault / panic room</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-center text-sm text-cream/60 mt-8 italic">
        Camden Planning generally approves basements that don't extend beyond the building footprint and include lightwell access. Extending under the garden requires stronger justification.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Technical Considerations -->
  <section class="section-padding">
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-12 text-center">Technical Challenges We Navigate</h2>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-3 text-oxidized-copper">1. Waterproofing Strategies</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            London clay is impermeable—water doesn't drain naturally. We specify multi-layer systems:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li><strong>Type A (Barrier):</strong> Bitumen/membrane - cheapest but risky if breached</li>
            <li><strong>Type B (Integral):</strong> Waterproof concrete - good for new-builds</li>
            <li><strong>Type C (Cavity Drainage):</strong> Mesh cavity + sump pump - gold standard for retrofits</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic mt-4">
            We typically specify Type C for Victorian terraces—it's forgiving if minor cracks appear.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-3 text-oxidized-copper">2. Underpinning Sequencing</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            You can't excavate the entire basement at once—the walls would collapse. We use sequenced underpinning:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Dig 1-meter sections in alternating pattern</li>
            <li>• Pour concrete foundations for each section</li>
            <li>• Wait 7 days for curing before next section</li>
            <li>• Monitor neighbour's walls with crack gauges</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic mt-4">
            Process takes 8-12 weeks for single-depth, 16-20 weeks for double-depth.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-3 text-oxidized-copper">3. Structural Steel Strategy</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Once you excavate beneath ground floor walls, you need steel beams to transfer the load:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Universal Beams (UB) support party walls</li>
            <li>• Padstones distribute load onto new foundations</li>
            <li>• Columns in basement minimize beam spans</li>
            <li>• Fire protection required (intumescent paint or boarding)</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic mt-4">
            Steelwork alone can cost £15-80k depending on span and loads.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-warm-stone p-6 border border-charcoal/10">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-medium mb-3 text-oxidized-copper">4. Soil Removal Logistics</h3>
          <p class="text-base text-charcoal/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            A 40m³ basement generates 60-80 tonnes of soil. Removal is non-trivial:
          </p>
          <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 text-charcoal/70">
            <li>• Soil conveyor through house (destroys hallway temporarily)</li>
            <li>• Skip wagon on street (requires council permit)</li>
            <li>• Muck-away costs: £25-40 per tonne</li>
            <li>• Reinstatement of floors/walls after removal</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-sm text-charcoal/70 italic mt-4">
            Neighbours will complain about noise/dust. Managing expectations is critical.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Case Studies Placeholder -->
  <section class="section-padding bg-warm-stone">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-serif font-light mb-8 text-center">Select Case Studies</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-charcoal/10">
